Woodhouse,
who
had
previously
made
up
his
mind
to
walk
out,
was
persuaded
by
his
daughter
not
to
defer
it,
and
was
induced
by
the
entreaties
of
both,
though
against
the
scruples
of
his
own
civility,
to
leave
Mr.
Knightley
for
that
purpose.
Mr.
Knightley,
who
had
nothing
of
ceremony
about
him,
was
offering
by
his
short,
decided
answers,
an
amusing
contrast
to
the
protracted
apologies
and
civil
hesitations
of
the
other.
"Well,
I
believe,
if
you
will
excuse
me,
Mr.
Knightley,
if
you
will
not
consider
me
as
doing
a
very
rude
thing,
I
shall
take
Emma's
advice
and
go
out
for
a
quarter
of
an
hour.
As
the
sun
is
out,
I
believe
I
had
better
take
my
three
turns
while
I
can.
I
treat
you
without
ceremony,
Mr.
Knightley.
We
invalids
think
we
are
privileged
people."
"My
dear
sir,
do
not
make
a
stranger
of
me."
"I
leave
an
excellent
substitute
in
my
daughter.
Emma
will
be
happy
to
entertain
you.
And
therefore
I
think
I
will
beg
your
excuse
and
take
my
three
turns
my
winter
walk."
"You
cannot
do
better,
sir."
"I
would
ask
for
the
pleasure
of
your
company,
